---
import BaseLayout from '@layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import InternalLinkStrip from '@components/modules/InternalLinkStrip.astro';

const title = 'How Hot Is Too Hot for Dogs?';
const description =
  'A practical temperature guide for dog owners: when heat is safe, when to take caution, and how to protect your dog from overheating.';
const pageSlug = 'how-hot-is-too-hot-for-dogs';

const internalLinks = [
  { label: 'Best Cooling Mats', href: '/cooling/cooling-mats/' },
  { label: 'Best Cooling Vests', href: '/cooling/cooling-vests/' },
  { label: 'Best Cooling Bandanas', href: '/cooling/cooling-bandanas/' },
  { label: 'Freezable Dog Toys', href: '/cooling/freezable-dog-toys/' },
];
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <article class="collector-article container">
    <header class="article-header">
      <span class="eyebrow">Cooling &amp; Safety</span>
      <h1>{title}</h1>
      <p class="lede">{description}</p>
    </header>

    <div class="prose">
      <h2>Why dogs overheat faster than humans</h2>
      <p>
        Dogs can't cool themselves the way humans do. We sweat across the entire surface of our skin;
        dogs primarily pant and release heat through their paw pads. That's a much smaller surface area,
        which means heat builds up quickly — especially in humid weather when panting becomes less effective.
        Flat-faced breeds (like Bulldogs and Pugs), older dogs, overweight dogs, and very young puppies
        are at even higher risk because their airways are narrower or their temperature regulation is less efficient.
      </p>

      <h2>Temperature risk chart</h2>
      <p>
        Outdoor air temperature is a starting point, but humidity, sun exposure, and activity level all
        increase the real feel for your dog. Use this as a general guide:
      </p>

      <div class="temp-chart" role="table" aria-label="Dog heat risk by temperature">
        <div class="temp-row temp-row--header" role="row">
          <span role="columnheader">Temperature</span>
          <span role="columnheader">Risk level</span>
          <span role="columnheader">What to do</span>
        </div>
        <div class="temp-row temp-row--safe" role="row">
          <span role="cell"><strong>70–80 °F</strong></span>
          <span role="cell" class="badge badge--safe">Safe</span>
          <span role="cell">Normal outdoor activity is fine. Keep water available.</span>
        </div>
        <div class="temp-row temp-row--caution" role="row">
          <span role="cell"><strong>80–85 °F</strong></span>
          <span role="cell" class="badge badge--caution">Caution</span>
          <span role="cell">Shorten exercise, avoid peak afternoon sun, offer water frequently.</span>
        </div>
        <div class="temp-row temp-row--high" role="row">
          <span role="cell"><strong>85–90 °F</strong></span>
          <span role="cell" class="badge badge--high">High risk</span>
          <span role="cell">Limit outdoor time to early morning or evening. Use cooling gear.</span>
        </div>
        <div class="temp-row temp-row--danger" role="row">
          <span role="cell"><strong>90 °F+</strong></span>
          <span role="cell" class="badge badge--danger">Dangerous</span>
          <span role="cell">Keep dogs indoors in air conditioning as much as possible.</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2>Pavement temperature warning</h2>
      <p>
        Air temperature does not tell the whole story. Asphalt and concrete absorb and radiate heat far beyond
        ambient air temperature. When it's 85 °F outside, blacktop can reach <strong>135 °F</strong> — hot
        enough to cause burns in under a minute.
      </p>
      <p>
        A simple test: press the back of your hand against the pavement for seven seconds. If you can't hold it
        there comfortably, it's too hot for your dog's paws. Walk on grass where possible, or stick to early
        morning and late evening walks.
      </p>

      <h2>Signs your dog is overheating</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Heavy, rapid panting</strong> that doesn't slow down with rest</li>
        <li><strong>Excessive drooling</strong> or thick, sticky saliva</li>
        <li><strong>Bright red gums or tongue</strong></li>
        <li><strong>Lethargy or weakness</strong> — stumbling or reluctance to move</li>
        <li><strong>Vomiting or diarrhea</strong></li>
        <li><strong>Glazed or unfocused eyes</strong></li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        If you see multiple signs at once, move your dog to a cool, shaded area immediately, offer small amounts
        of cool (not ice-cold) water, and contact your vet. Heatstroke can escalate quickly and requires
        prompt professional care.
      </p>

      <h2>How to keep your dog cool</h2>
      <p>
        The right gear can make a real difference during hot months. These popular options cover the most
        practical approaches to keeping dogs cool:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Cooling mats</strong> — pressure-activated gel pads designed for indoor or outdoor use.</li>
        <li><strong>Cooling vests</strong> — evaporative or reflective wraps intended to lower body temperature during walks.</li>
        <li><strong>Cooling bandanas</strong> — a lightweight, budget-friendly option for shorter outings.</li>
        <li><strong>Freezable toys</strong> — frozen treat dispensers that provide enrichment and help with internal cooling.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <InternalLinkStrip links={internalLinks} fromPage={pageSlug} />
  </article>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .collector-article {
    padding-top: var(--space-3xl);
    padding-bottom: var(--space-4xl);
    max-width: var(--max-width-prose);
  }

  .article-header {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2xl);
  }

  .eyebrow {
    display: inline-block;
    font-size: var(--text-xs);
    font-weight: 700;
    letter-spacing: 0.14em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--color-accent);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-sm);
  }

  .article-header h1 {
    font-size: var(--text-4xl);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-md);
  }

  .lede {
    font-size: var(--text-lg);
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
  }

  .prose h2 {
    font-size: var(--text-2xl);
    margin-top: var(--space-2xl);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-md);
  }

  .prose p,
  .prose ul {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-md);
    line-height: 1.7;
  }

  .prose ul {
    padding-left: var(--space-lg);
  }

  .prose li {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-sm);
  }

  /* Temperature chart */
  .temp-chart {
    display: grid;
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-radius: var(--radius-lg);
    overflow: hidden;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-xl);
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
  }

  .temp-row {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 9rem 8rem 1fr;
    gap: var(--space-md);
    padding: var(--space-sm) var(--space-md);
    align-items: center;
  }

  .temp-row--header {
    font-weight: 700;
    font-size: var(--text-xs);
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    background: var(--color-bg-alt);
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
  }

  .temp-row:not(.temp-row--header) {
    border-top: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  }

  .badge {
    display: inline-block;
    padding: 0.2rem 0.6rem;
    border-radius: 999px;
    font-weight: 700;
    font-size: var(--text-xs);
    letter-spacing: 0.04em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
  }

  .badge--safe {
    background: rgba(104, 160, 133, 0.16);
    color: #2e6448;
  }

  .badge--caution {
    background: rgba(201, 185, 82, 0.22);
    color: #7a6200;
  }

  .badge--high {
    background: rgba(201, 138, 82, 0.18);
    color: #8a4e1d;
  }

  .badge--danger {
    background: rgba(200, 70, 70, 0.14);
    color: #8b1a1a;
  }

  @media (max-width: 640px) {
    .article-header h1 {
      font-size: var(--text-3xl);
    }

    .temp-row {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
      gap: var(--space-xs);
    }

    .temp-row--header {
      display: none;
    }
  }
</style>
